  "texts": [
    "It is not my intention to fully endorse the Aristotelian picture of moral competence.",
    "Indeed, I do not know if there is a single such picture, and if there is, I have left out many relevant aspects.",
    "Rather, I wish to stress that moral sensitivity, characterised by the above three features, appears at least as part of our moral competence, once we reflect on our commonsense moral practices.",
    "First, our moral duties, especially towards people to whom we stand in personal relationships, often rest on qualitatively unique features, such as the shape of a specific relationship.",
    "Second, common experience bears out that moral competence cannot be taught only by feeding someone propositional knowledge; rather, people require guided training by morally competent adults to become themselves morally competent."
  ],
